<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-060-080 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 330 891</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Sept 13 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Versatile new Philips CD/CD-ROM player. (Philips ConsumerElectronics debuts Magnavox CDD461RS) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McCormick, John.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Philips Consumer Electronics Co. (Product introduction).andO;Product:   Philips Consumer Electronics Magnavox CDD461RS (CD-ROM drive)(Product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionCD-ROMHome EntertainmentDisk Drives.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>****VERSATILE NEW PHILIPS CD/CD-ROM PLAYER 09/13/91 KNOXVILLE, TENNESSEE,U.S.A., 1991 SEP 13 (NB) -- Philips Consumer Electronics has taken a lead inthe CD-ROM industry by recognizing that, since the CD audio player and theCD-ROM are closely related, it would make sense to combine the two in a newand useful way.andM;In the past, CD-ROM players often came with audio outputs and, by addingsoftware, not to mention a full computer, people could play audio discseither through headphones or a stereo system.andM;Now Philips Consumer Electronics has introduced the Magnavox CDD461RS, astand-alone CD audio player that can also be connected to your computer butone which puts the audio features first.andM;The CDD461RS lets users play music through their stereo without turning on anassociated computer or running special software.andM;The designers of this 10-pound unit didn't forget the computer market, sincethe player is built strong enough to mount under a monitor if desired, but,unlike all other CD-ROM drives, it also includes front panel controls forplaying music discs.andM;Priced at $549, it comes with hardware and software for XT- compatiblesystems, the drive itself, and a set of CD-ROM discs including MicrosoftBookshelf and the New Grolier Electronic Encyclopedia.andP;  The system is aimedat the customer who Philips believes normally uses the CD-ROM player only 10percent of the time as a data device and 90 percent of the time to playmusic.andM;While the new drive adds something new (the audio drive controls) it alsoleft something out, the disc caddy that many drives require.andP;  Returning tothe older CD-ROM style as exemplified by the Amdek/Hitachi drives, this unithas a drawer that you drop a CD or CD-ROM into, rather than a separate disccarrier that must be loaded and then inserted in the drive.andM;(John McCormick/19910913/Press Contact: Michelle Zawronty, HWH PR,212-355-5049)</TEXT></DOC>